<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-305-838  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 305 838.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  March 19 1990 v36 n1801 p13(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CPE firms vow fight vs. ATandamp;T bundling. (customer premisesequipment vendors will fight moves to alter restrictionspreventing ATandamp;T from bundling CPE equipment with regulatedservices)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lefton, Terry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Customer premises equipment (CPE) vendors will fight any moves theFCC might make to alter restrictions that forbid ATandamp;T frombundling CPE equipment with regulated services.andP;  The CPE vendorsbelieve that altering the regulations would return thetelecommunications industry to monopolistic control.andP;  ATandamp;T hasasked the commission to determine if it could still be classifiedas a 'dominant carrier' in the long distance market.andP;  As adominant carrier, the company must adhere to regulations to whichits competitors are not subject, including the prohibitionconcerning bundling.andP;  ATandamp;T has approximately 25 percent of thedomestic CPE market and 60 percent of the installed base.andP;  Despitea declining market share, some believe that ATandamp;T can leverage CPEwith regulated services; the company remains dominant in otherservice markets.andP;  Some also fear that regional Bell operatingcompanies will follow ATandamp;T's lead.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (rules and regulations).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionCompetitionTelecommunicationsRegulationCustomer Premises EquipmentMarket Share.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>